example.p:
Evaluating the integral is non-trivial, but here is an overview.  When working with floor/ceiling functions, one trick is to assume your variable satisfies inequalities that explicitly give a formula for their value.  In this case, we assume that  k is some positive integer.
\begin{split}
	2[\frac{1}{x}]=2k &\Leftrightarrow  [\frac{1}{x}]=k\\
	                & \Leftrightarrow k \leq \frac{1}{x} \lt k +1 \\
	 						& \Leftrightarrow \frac{1}{k+1} \lt x \leq \frac{1}{k}
	 			\end{split}

\begin{split}
		 k \leq \frac{1}{x} \le k +1  &\Leftrightarrow 2k \leq \frac{2}{x} \le 2k +2 \\
											&\Leftrightarrow  \left[\frac{2}{x}\right] = 2k \textrm{ or } 2k + 1.
	\end{split}
If \frac{1}{k+1} \lt x \leq \frac{2}{2k+1}, we have [\frac{2}{x}] = 2k+1; and if \frac{2}{2k+1} \lt x \leq \frac{1}{k}, we have [\frac{2}{x}] = 2k.  Therefore,  on the interval (\frac{1}{k+1}, \frac{1}{k}], 

f(x)==\begin{cases} 1 & \textrm{if } \frac{1}{k+1} \lt x \leq \frac{2}{2k+1}\\
							0 & \textrm{if } \frac{2}{2k+1} \lt x \leq \frac{1}{k}
							\end{cases}

and \int_{\frac{1}{k+1}}^{\frac{1}{k}} f(x) dx = \frac{2}{2k+1}-  \frac{1}{k+1}

statement.p:
Prove the following or provide a counterexample:  If \left\{f_n\right\} is a sequence of functions defined on the interval [0,1] and that
for each \textit{ x} in the interval \lim_{n\to \infty } f_n(x) = f(x),  then    \lim_{n\to \infty } \int_0^1 f_n(x) \, dx=\int_0^1 f(x)
\, dx.
